description.narrative:
SAfAIDS in partnership with Sonke Gender Justice implemented a 2-year gender norms transformative programme that sought to transform gender roles and promote more gender-equitable relationships between young men and young women to reduce HIV, GBV and promote positive SRH within hard to reach areas like farms and mining communities in Zimbabwe. This programme was implemented in Chiredzi, Hwange, Nyanga and Seke districts in partnership with Fact Chiredzi (FACT), Buwalo Matalikilo Trust (BMT), Diocese of Mutare Community Care Project (DOMCCP) and Seke Rural Home Based Care (SRHBC) respectively.
Drawing on Sonke Gender Justice’s experience in gender norms transformation approaches, the two organisations collaborated to build the capacity of SAfAIDS and its partners, and other institutions to effectively integrate and undertake gender norms transformative programming that engages men and boys in addressing GBV and HIV, and promoting positive SRHR outcomes. 
The resluts achieved included capacity strengthening of SAFAIDS staff and implementing partners om gender norms transfomration, at the same time building communities ability to cascade work with men and boys in and out of school as well community level dialogues targeting leaders and parents. Strategic national and regional activities included evidence generation, policy maker’s sensitisation meetings on gender norms transformation, technical assistance in the development of the Zimbabwe Adolescent Sexual and Reproductive Health strategy 2016-2020 as well as hosting of a regional symposium working with leadership, men and boys.  
Activities conducted over the two-year implementation period sought to achieve the programme goal through the following 5 specific objectives: 
       I.        Strengthened capacity of SAfAIDS and its 4 local partners by Sonke on gender norms transformation (including work on engaging men and boys) theory, programme implementation, monitoring and evaluation, in Zimbabwe by 2017; 
    II.        Strengthened capacity of 720 young people (10-24years), both females and males, in and out of schools (24 schools in 6 per district) to practice equitable gender norms, practices and attitudes that reduce HIV and GBV, and impact positively on their SRHR outcomes, in Zimbabwe by 2017; 
   III.        Strengthened capacity of 300 community leaders (including religious and traditional leaders) and 200 parents to reduce harmful cultural and religious practices that promote inequitable gender norms, risk for HIV and GBV among young people, both females and males, in Zimbabwe by 2017; 
  IV.        Undertake policy advocacy and provide technical input into national policy review and development processes , and 
    V.        Evidence generated, to promote innovation and learning on gender transformation to address HIV, GBV prevention among young people (females and males), in Zimbabwe by 2017.
